04803nam a22006855i 9781503607392DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202018cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2018013070  a97815036073927 a10.1515/97815036073922doi  a(DE-B1597)563762  a(OCoLC)1178768875  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aE185.615b.F527 2019 4aE185.615b.F527 2019 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a323.1196/0732231 aFischbach, Michael R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBlack Power and Palestine :bTransnational Countries of Color /cMichael R. Fischbach. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStanford Studies in Comparative Race and Ethnicity00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACRONYMS -- tPROLOGUE -- tChapter 1. BLACK INTERNATIONALISM -- tChapter 2. THE FIRE THIS TIME -- tChapter 3. REFORMERS, NOT REVOLUTIONARIES -- tChapter 4. BALANCED AND GUARDED -- tChapter 5. THE POWER OF WORDS -- tChapter 6. STRUGGLE AND REVOLUTION -- tChapter 7. MIDDLE EAST SYMBIOSIS -- tChapter 8. RED, WHITE, AND BLACK -- tChapter 9. A SEAT AT THE TABLE -- tChapter 10. LOOKING OVER JORDAN -- tEPILOGUE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe 1967 Arab-Israeli War rocketed the question of Israel and Palestine onto the front pages of American newspapers. Black Power activists saw Palestinians as a kindred people of color, waging the same struggle for freedom and justice as themselves. Soon concerns over the Arab-Israeli conflict spread across mainstream black politics and into the heart of the civil rights movement itself. Black Power and Palestine uncovers why so many African Americans-notably Martin Luther King, Jr., Malcolm X, and Muhammad Ali, among others-came to support the Palestinians or felt the need to respond to those who did. Americans first heard pro-Palestinian sentiments in public through the black freedom struggle of the 1960s and 1970s. Michael R. Fischbach uncovers this hidden history of the Arab-Israeli conflict's role in African American activism and the ways that distant struggle shaped the domestic fight for racial equality. Black Power's transnational connections between African Americans and Palestinians deeply affected U.S. black politics, animating black visions of identity well into the late 1970s. Black Power and Palestine allows those black voices to be heard again today. In chronicling this story, Fischbach reveals much about how American peoples of color create political strategies, a sense of self, and a place within U.S. and global communities. The shadow cast by events of the 1960s and 1970s continues to affect the United States in deep, structural ways. This is the first book to explore how conflict in the Middle East shaped the American civil rights movement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAfrican American civil rights workersxAttitudes. 0aArab-Israeli conflictxForeign public opinion, American. 0aArab-Israeli conflicty1967-1973xInfluence. 0aBlack powerzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aCivil rights movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPublic opinionzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aAfrican Americans. 4aArab-Israeli conflict. 4aBlack Power. 4aIsrael. 4aMartin Luther King Jr. 4aPalestinians. 4aTransnational. 4acivil rights. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360739240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503607392423Coveruhttp